          "body": "The chapter's military section unfolds in carefully escalating 'in that day' promises. First, enemy horses are struck with bewilderment and blindness while God watches over Judah (12:4) — the asymmetry of the battle is total from the start. Second, the clans of Judah become a firepot and flaming torch among the surrounding peoples (12:6) — they do not merely survive but consume. Third, Judah is saved first, before Jerusalem's élite, so that no internal glory contest distorts the deliverance (12:7). Fourth — and this is the chapter's military apex — the feeble inhabitant of Jerusalem becomes like David, and the house of David like God, like the Angel of the LORD going before them (12:8). The escalation is deliberate: individual → clan → city → dynasty, each level supernaturally elevated above what it was. The comparison to the Angel of the LORD is especially striking. In Exodus 23:20-23, the Angel of the LORD went before Israel to defeat the Canaanites; at the end of history, the house of David will be elevated to that same vanguard function. The military section closes with the declaration that God will seek to destroy all nations that come against Jerusalem (12:9) — a verse that is at once the military conclusion and the hinge that makes verse 10 possible."
