        "excerpt": "I will pour out on the house of David and on the inhabitants of Jerusalem, the Spirit of grace and of supplication, so that they will look on Me whom they have pierced.",
        "body": "Verse 10 is the chapter's theological climax and one of the most important single verses in the Old Testament for its Christological and pneumatological weight. It is structured as a divine act with a result clause: God pours out the Spirit *so that* they look and mourn. The causation runs from God to Spirit to sight to grief. There is no possibility of the looking happening without the Spirit's outpouring, and no possibility of the Spirit's outpouring happening without God's sovereign initiative. The mourning is entirely grace-produced.\n\nThe Spirit poured out is characterized by two nouns: *chen* (grace, favor, unmerited acceptance) and *tachanun* (supplication, earnest petitioning). The Spirit of grace produces the experience of being freely accepted by God; the Spirit of supplication produces the cry of the penitent who knows he needs that grace. The combination describes the interior of genuine conversion: the soul that has been given grace turns immediately into a soul that pleads for it. Joel 2:28-29 uses the same verb (*shaphakh*, pour out) for the Spirit promised before the day of the LORD; Acts 2:17-21 identifies Pentecost as that pouring. Whether Zechariah 12:10 is the same event as Joel's pouring (inaugurated at Pentecost and continuing) or a distinct future pouring on national Israel is a major exegetical question on which premillennial and amillennial interpreters divide. Premillennial interpreters (e.g., Charles Feinberg, Thomas McComiskey) read 12:10 as a future national conversion of Israel distinct from the church age, anchored to a literal return of Christ to Jerusalem. Amillennial interpreters (e.g., Meredith Kline) read the passage as fulfilled in principle at Pentecost and the church age, with the 'house of David' and 'Jerusalem' functioning as typological designations for the new covenant community. Both views must reckon with John 19:37 and Revelation 1:7.\n\nThe grammatical crux of verse 10 is the pronoun shift: 'they will look on *Me* whom they have pierced; and they will mourn for *Him*.' The LORD speaks in first person ('Me pierced') and then describes the mourning in third person ('for Him'). This has been explained as (a) a scribal error, (b) a deliberate shift to the transcendence of God who cannot be directly addressed in His grief, (c) an early indication of the distinction-within-unity that the NT will reveal as the Son distinguished from the Father. The LXX renders the clause 'they shall look upon me, because they have mocked me,' softening the piercing; the MT's *daqar* (to thrust through with a weapon) is unambiguous. John 19:37's direct quotation of the MT against the LXX is decisive: the apostle reads the verse as a literal piercing, fulfilled in the lance thrust into Jesus's side, and anticipates its fuller national fulfillment in the future.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shaphakh* (pour out, v.10) — the verb for pouring out wrath (Psalm 79:6; Lamentations 2:4), blood (Genesis 9:6), and Spirit (Joel 2:28). Its use for the Spirit is an act of radical divine generosity — the same intensity as wrath, directed as grace. *Chen* (grace) — the unmerited favor that characterizes God's covenant dealings; *tachanun* — from *chanan* (to be gracious); the plural form denotes urgent, repeated petitions for mercy. *Daqar* (pierced) — to thrust through with a spear or sword; used of Saul's death (1 Samuel 31:4) and violent killing (Numbers 25:8). Never metaphorical — always physical violence."
